    <p>Your statement is partly true but chemically misleading. The distinction you’re drawing (“glutamate is natural, MSG is manufactured”) sounds intuitive, but it doesn’t survive scrutiny once chemistry and food biochemistry are applied.</p>

    <p><strong>MSG = sodium + glutamate.</strong></p>

    <p>In solution (like saliva, soup, or your stomach), MSG dissociates immediately into sodium ions and free glutamate. The body cannot tell whether that glutamate came from a tomato, cheese, seaweed, or added MSG.</p>

    <p>Modern MSG production uses microbial fermentation, the same class of process used to make yogurt, vinegar, soy sauce, beer, cheese, insulin, and citric acid.</p>

    <p>Calling MSG “manufactured” does not make it petrochemical or biologically different. The difference is quantitative, not qualitative.</p>
